```rust
fn avg(arr: &[f64]) -> f64 {
    let sum = arr.iter().sum::<f64>();
    sum / arr.len() as f64
}
```

Rust’s `f64` type follows IEEE 754 double-precision, so it behaves similarly to Java or Python doubles. Other languages might offer alternative types like decimal or arbitrary precision numbers, but Rust doesn’t natively support those.

One approach is to manually round the result:
```rust
fn avg(arr: &[f64]) -> f64 {
    let sum = arr.iter().sum::<f64>();
    (sum / arr.len() as f64).round(5)
}
```
But note that rounding introduces another layer of error.

